body:
i found this while building a small utility that renames tmux windows based on certain user actions: an anchored `s///` format substitution that matches empty at the start of the string deletes the first character of the input, and never expands the replacement.

repro on a clean server:

```
tmux -f /dev/null -L test new-session -d
tmux -L test set -g @v "abc"
tmux -L test display-message -p '#{s/^x*//:@v}'    # bc  (expected abc)
tmux -L test display-message -p '#{s/^/y/:@v}'     # bc  (expected yabc)
tmux -L test display-message -p '#{s/^x*/y/:@v}'   # bc  (expected yabc)
```

- master @ 1d70211 (next-3.8), also reproduces on next-3.7
- macos 26.5.1, apple silicon
- unanchored patterns are unaffected: `#{s/x*//:@v}` gives `abc`; `#{s/^x+//:@v}` is also correct

cause: in regsub(), an empty match takes the skip-one-character path and advances `start` past the unmatched character; copying that character is deferred to the next iteration, which copies from `last`:

```c
	} else {
		last = start + m[0].rm_eo;
		start += m[0].rm_eo + 1;
		empty = 1;
	}

	/* Stop now if anchored to start. */
	if (*pattern == '^') {
		regsub_copy(&buf, &len, text, start, end);
		break;
	}
```

the anchored early-exit (from 20c1f1ae) copies from `start` instead of `last` and breaks, so the character between `last` and `start` never reaches the output, and the replacement for the empty match is never expanded

present since 20c1f1ae (2019)
